      "business_constraints": {
        "assistant_drafted_requirements_count": 13,
        "assistant_drafted_requirements_summary": "Expose a governed GitHub capability surface instead of raw GitHub operations: The product shall provide an ANIP fronting service for GitHub that exposes business-safe repository capabilities rather than raw GitHub REST, GraphQL, or tool-level operations. The contract shall own the capability semantics presented to agents and callers, while native GitHub APIs remain the backend integration surface.\nSupport bounded repository context search and inspection within explicit repository scope: The product shall support read-only repository context access for allowed repositories, including bounded issue and pull request search using explicit repository inputs such as owner, repo, and query. Results shall return bounded summaries rather than raw repository export or unbounded codebase data.\nProvide issue preparation as a preview-first flow with governed inputs: The product shall allow a caller to prepare a GitHub issue using explicit repository scope and issue fields, including title and body, with governed optional fields such as labels, assignees, and milestone. The preparation step shall return a preview suitable for review and approval rather than directly creating the issue.\nRequire explicit approval before any governed GitHub mutation is executed: The product shall not execute issue creation, pull request comment posting, workflow dispatch, or release publication without explicit approval. For mutation requests, the system shall stop at a reviewable preview or request state until approval is granted, and shall preserve the approval boundary in the contract behavior.\nSupport governed pull request comment preparation without direct posting: The product shall support preparation of pull request comments from review or release context using explicit repository and pull request identifiers. The output shall be a preview-only comment draft, with posting blocked until approval is granted.\nGate workflow dispatch requests and restrict sensitive workflows: The product shall support requesting a GitHub Actions workflow run using explicit repository, workflow, and ref inputs, but shall treat dispatch as approval-gated. Workflows designated as restricted shall require explicit grant handling beyond the base request flow, and the system shall not allow workflow bypass through backend options or direct backend access.\nGenerate release notes as bounded drafts without publishing releases: The product shall support drafting release notes from bounded repository context such as issue, pull request, milestone, or comparison data using an explicit release range. The capability shall produce draft output only and shall not create or publish a GitHub release.\nReturn clarification_required when required repository or operation context is missing: The product shall return clarification_required when a request lacks the repository, pull request, workflow, or release range context needed to safely execute the governed capability. The system shall not infer missing scope or proceed with partial context for governed operations.\nDeny unsafe or out-of-bounds GitHub operations at the contract level: The product shall explicitly deny secret exfiltration, raw file export, unbounded repository export, unbounded codebase dumps, arbitrary mutation payload passthrough, and direct workflow bypass. These denials shall be part of the governed contract rather than left to backend behavior alone.\nConstrain backend options to bounded provider features only: If backend_options are exposed, they shall be limited to bounded provider features such as selected fields, pagination, or expand-like metadata. backend_options shall not permit arbitrary mutation payloads, secret access, workflow bypass, or unbounded data extraction.\nMake repository allowlists and enterprise control posture explicit: The product shall make allowed organization and repository scope explicit and enforce it consistently across all governed capabilities. The service design shall reflect centralized enterprise identity, repository allowlists, approval records, and audit expectations as first-class control mechanisms.\nRecord audit metadata for previews, approvals, denials, and backend execution: The product shall preserve audit metadata that allows reviewers to understand what capability was requested, what repository scope applied, whether the request was previewed, approved, denied, clarified, or executed, and which backend GitHub operation was used. Audit behavior shall be explicit in the contract and service expectations.\nBind execution to native GitHub REST and GraphQL integrations, not MCP: The product shall use native GitHub REST and GraphQL APIs as the execution binding for this package. MCP may be referenced only as a comparison point for raw tool exposure and shall not be treated as the required ANIP execution interface."
      }
    }
